description:
Kris' parents retraced Kris' steps here at the start of August 2014. So 4 months after their daughter's disappearance. My blog about this disappearance case: https://koudekaas.blogspot.com/
With regards to the tile only mentioning Kris (and not Lisanne): This video was shot and made by the parents of Kris. I only added English subtitles to the Dutch video. In August of 2014 they went to Boquete to recreate their daughter's steps. The parents of Kris and Lisanne by then no longer worked together, respectively, because they had different beliefs about what may have happened. So Lisanne's parents cooperated with a Dutch tv program (Break Free) to highlight their daughters travel and passing, and they did not mention Kris much either. It is just what they decided, not in anger but both families just had different ideas and wanted to respectfully do their own research. Kris' parents also started a law case against the Panamanian case officials, while the Froon family did not.

Also check out Juan's many and good videos on the case: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCaTotobvErxwF5xcW5wxYlg/videos
All the translated videos about this case I put in this playlist: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLDldKFcWBW3oKYfjz8zvNGa9U6ezj-rvk

! It is wrong and horrible to threaten someone who is always innocent until proven otherwise. Stop that and leave this man alone in his life and on his socials. It is the poor investigation that is to blame for the info vacuum this case has gotten stuck in. But critical questions should always be allowed to be asked out loud.

comments.text: This is such an awful story. It is really haunting. I truly feel for the parents. It is so hard to speculate what the girls might/might not have done and whether they came to harm through natural events or something else. Playing armchair detective is pretty silly but, as a hiking guide, lots of things make me wonder about their story. The first thing is what time did they REALLY start hiking the trail. Morning around 10-11 am (as seems to be the case from their photos) or early afternoon, as the taxi driver who dropped them off states. How many daylight hours would you have left and how would that inform you decision about whether to turn back or carry on? I understand the parents saying 'why didn't they take any photos from here, it's so beautiful?' but I don't really think it tells us much (taken enough pics,  too tired to get your camera out of your backpack, can't be bothered...there are some many reasons).  Something like a sprained ankle could be catastrophic enough, as it impedes one from walking and doesn't leave enough time to return via the way you came in daylight hours), why didn't they split up and the uninjured person try to seek help? I have no idea what happened to them and it's useless to speculate but what an awful way to die and how horrific for the parents, who will probably never get closure.

In the disappearance of these two Dutch girls, there are two situations that I don't understand and I believe that need a more careful analysis:
1-If in the first two calls to the Dutch emergency number, they were already under the control of kidnappers, why didn't the criminals take the phones, the camera and all their belongings?

This doesn't make any sense! No offenders with murderous or sexual intentions would risk being photographed by their victims, or even risk the girls calling the police or leaving a message recorded on their cell phones for when they are found by the authorities.

2- Why don't you have any attempt to call 911 during the night?

What would be the worst moment for two girls from an urban environment, lost in the middle of a tropical jungle?
Do you agree with me that this worst moment would be to spend the night in the forest?! Exhausted, cold, with animals moving on the ground, animal movement in the dark forest, a plague of insects, rain spray, hunger, thirst and darkness everywhere. There are too many unanswered questions to make serious conclusions about the events that took place after the last photo, but the fact they began making emergency calls about 2-3 hours after the picture at the creek tells me (1) they were likely not abducted at that time and (2) they realized they needed help, i.e., they were probably lost. So, my best guess is they left the trail for unknown (but important) reasons and (2) subsequently became lost and (3) likely wandered through the forest, finally finding the small river below and spent the next couple weeks in that area and probably tried exploring upstream in search of help/civilization. Based on everything else I have read, I would guess that they encountered a person or people while near the river who turned out to have criminal intent. The backpack was relatively undisturbed, apparently, and suggests that the 2 had set it aside as they bathed but then were either abducted or for some reason suddenly left it behind. The fact that the camera and cell phones were in the pack tells me the people responsible for harm were not sophisticated in nature. I have further speculations as to what happened, but I have extended my hypothesis beyond what is reasonable already. My sincerest condolences to the families, and thanks to all the wonderful volunteers from Panama who have tried to help.

comments.text:
I'm just going to play devil's advocate here.  I don't really KNOW what happened to these girls but I see a lot of swirling around bits of minutiae instead of looking at the totality of the evidence.  Granted, it isn't much, but there is so much more to consider.  I've seen people's lives destroyed through conjectures like this and I think there needs to be more care into how the people of the area are treated.  These are people born and raised in the jungle, possibly for generations.  They know the dangers of the area, how the jungle behaves in each season, how the river swells and recedes, and they know the general terrain like the back of their own hand.  They should be listened to.
I've never been to Central America but I have sure hiked through jungles in India.  The guides meet people from all over the world.  We are as strange to them as they are to us. They do their best to relate and communicate but they come from a very different culture. They are incredibly hard working, knowledgeable, and kind.  It makes no sense that a community would protect someone that jeopardizes their livelihoods and survival.  I've only found people in these small village communities to be on guard but kind and generous.  They have to size you up, too.  
I was on board with the sensationalism of this case and, because of that, believed that Kris and Lisanne were murdered.  However, after applying my own experiences, even though I may be leaning on the anecdotal, I have pivoted to the belief that the probability is they got lost.  The jungle is a very confusing place; wild, unpredictable, full of toxic plants and bugs, snakes, and just very dangerous if you don't know what those dangers are.  Just falling on a rock from a standing position can cause awful injuries inside and out. 
When you look at all the search units and police went through to find them, it's easier to see why they couldn't.  They have to respect the jungle with all its dangers, too, and some of the searches had to be curbed because it would be too dangerous for them.  There were a lot of injuries sustained, even from Pitti who still has a limp from the injuries she received from slogging through knee deep mud and falling.  In mountainous areas, clouds and fog move in it with an everchanging frequency which prohibits choppers from landing.  Even the dogs were in danger of foot rot from being damp all the time.  Jungle rot is a real thing--and that kind of exposure is dangerous for any creature not born to the climate.    All in all, the searchers all went through a lot to find them and I'm sure they all felt devastated that they didn't.  
Being exhausted, unslept, starved, and not properly hydrated will do things to you.  Even though they were by an ample water source, sweat makes you lose salt and causes electrolyte imbalances.  Exhaustion makes you more susceptible to injury and I'm sure their judgement became very clouded quickly.  The mind begins to hallucinate which makes it all much, much worse.  These poor woman seemed to have really put up a fight to stay alive. I'm so sad and sorry for them and their loved ones.  It's a very, very sad tale and I'm sure the community feels partly responsible.  I know it's en vogue to dunk on police, but the vast majority of them are good people doing the best job they can.  It's only the bad ones that get in the news and we can't let that notoriety cloud our judgement about them.  I believe in the principle of good faith and there are too many people treating this as a bad episode of 'Columbo'.  It makes zero sense that criminals would allow them to have their cell phones.  All evidence would have been well disposed of.  Even with the little disparities of the case that seem peculiar do not point to foul play to me.  During monsoon season, flash flooding is very prevalent--and it does make sense that the remains would have been carried all over the place.  As the river settles back down and recedes, it does stand to reason that debris would be left scattered everywhere.  I could go on.  Every point can be countered.  Either way, we cannot bring those two women back.  Rest in peace, Lisanne and Kris.  Wishing all of their loved ones peace and healing.
